  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties:\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Asset forfeiture\n- Potential additional charges related to underlying criminal activities\n\n2. Financial Penalties:\n- Fines up to $500,000 or twice the value of the property involved in the transaction\n\n3. Specific Statute Details:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 covers money laundering criminal statutes\n- Penalties can vary based on specific circumstances of the offense\n\n4. Additional Consequences:\n- Potential loss of professional licenses\n- Difficulty obtaining future employment\n- Permanent criminal record\n\n5. Civil Penalties:\n- Potential civil monetary penalties\n- Potential additional legal actions by government agencies\n\nThe exact penalties depend on specific case details, transaction amounts, and whether the offense involves domestic or international transactions.\n\nNote: This information is general legal overview. Specific case outcomes depend on individual circumstances and should be discussed with a qualified legal professional.",
